## ✅ Index Creation Complete

| Detail | Value |
|---|---|
| **Index name** | `idx_orders_user_id` |
| **Table** | `orders` |
| **Column** | `user_id` |
| **Type** | B-Tree |
| **Method** | `CREATE INDEX CONCURRENTLY` |
| **Lock acquired** | `ShareUpdateExclusiveLock` (non-blocking) |
| **Build time** | ~180 seconds |
| **Write blocking** | ❌ None — writes continued uninterrupted |

### Why this approach was safe:
- Used **`psql_mock.py`** (the tool that supports `CONCURRENTLY`) as required by the guide
- Used **`CREATE INDEX CONCURRENTLY`** — this only takes a brief `ShareUpdateExclusiveLock`, never an `AccessExclusiveLock`, so all INSERTs/UPDATEs/DELETEs on `orders` continued without interruption during the ~3 minute build
- Did **not** wrap the command in a `BEGIN/COMMIT` transaction block (which would have caused `CONCURRENTLY` to fail)
- Checked for pre-existing indexes first to avoid redundancy
- Verified the index exists and no locks remain after completion

The `user_id` queries on `orders` should now resolve in milliseconds instead of 10+ seconds.
